{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"769321ee-bc03-48a9-9704-58b0168846c2","content":"The template has a solid foundation but has a few issues to address before publishing:\n\n**🔴 Functional Bug**\n- The `Framework` symbol has no `replaces` property. Choosing `net8.0` won't actually change the target framework in generated files. Add `\"replaces\": \"net9.0\"` to the symbol.\n\n**🟡 Recommended for NuGet**\n- **Missing `$schema`** — Add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for validation/editor support.\n- **Missing `description`** — NuGet gallery uses this for discoverability.\n- **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Important when publishing multiple related templates in one package.\n\n**✅ Looks Good**\n- `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `author`, `sourceName`, `classifications`, and `tags` are all properly set.\n\n**Verdict:** Not ready yet — at minimum fix the `Framework` → `replaces` bug, and add a `description`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bbd34047-94c8-4ce7-95e6-601e85e0ac02","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check against the .NET template engine schema requirements.\n\nIssues I can identify:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required, but strongly recommended for validation and editor support.\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet package templates, especially when you might have multiple related templates.\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Useful when multiple versions of the same template exist.\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Minor, but good practice.\n5. **`sourceName`** is set to `\"MyWebApi\"` — This is fine as long as the project/files use this name for replacement.\n\n\n6. **`defaultValue` for Framework is `\"net9.0\"`** — That works fine.\n7. **No `replaces`** in the Framework symbol — The Framework parameter defines choices but won't actually modify the target framework in the generated project files without a `replaces` property. For a framework chooser to work properly, you'd need something like `\"replaces\": \"net9.0\"` so the selected framework value actually gets substituted into the project configuration.\n\nThe key issues I'm seeing are:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Recommended but not critical.\n2. **Framework symbol missing `replaces`** — This is a real functional problem. Users can select `net8.0` but it won't change the `<TargetFramework>` in the `.csproj` file. The `replaces` property is essential for this to work.\n3. **Missing top-level `description`** — Not required but would help with NuGet discoverability.","outputTokens":719,"requestId":"2804:2110B5:1015A04:1413E43:69FFD939"},"id":"1b96047b-b0df-4bd4-b621-577e21d10c81","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:03:06.986Z","parentId":"092209c5-c958-40c6-95f7-1eef02d74ad8"}
